WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.485 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:02.485 --> 00:00:04.970 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:04.970 --> 00:00:07.455 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.455 --> 00:00:16.420 align:middle line:90%


00:00:16.420 --> 00:00:20.760 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: So let me continue
with the IS-LM-PC model.

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:25.240 align:middle line:84%
In fact, I want to rush a little
bit because I was overexcited

00:00:25.240 --> 00:00:27.760 align:middle line:90%
with the SVB bank event.

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:33.700 align:middle line:84%
And I want to make sure that you
certainly understand this model.

00:00:33.700 --> 00:00:36.940 align:middle line:90%
It's going to be very important.

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:40.870 align:middle line:84%
And I think it's one of the most
important models in this course,

00:00:40.870 --> 00:00:42.550 align:middle line:90%
as I said before.

00:00:42.550 --> 00:00:46.690 align:middle line:84%
Also, I want to use it a little
bit more, this model itself,

00:00:46.690 --> 00:00:48.590 align:middle line:84%
to explain what is
going on right now.

00:00:48.590 --> 00:00:52.250 align:middle line:84%
Today, we got hit by a second
shock from the financial system.

00:00:52.250 --> 00:00:57.920 align:middle line:84%
And so it's getting
exciting these days.

00:00:57.920 --> 00:01:01.870 align:middle line:84%
So let me skip all
this and remind you

00:01:01.870 --> 00:01:03.620 align:middle line:90%
that that's where we were.

00:01:03.620 --> 00:01:06.190 align:middle line:84%
That's the IS-LM-PC
model, which I

00:01:06.190 --> 00:01:10.750 align:middle line:84%
said is nothing else than just
integrating the IS-LM analysis

00:01:10.750 --> 00:01:12.080 align:middle line:90%
with the Phillips curve.

00:01:12.080 --> 00:01:13.520 align:middle line:90%
This is the IS part.

00:01:13.520 --> 00:01:16.860 align:middle line:84%
And I said at this point,
I will follow the book

00:01:16.860 --> 00:01:20.180 align:middle line:84%
and assume that the central bank
can control the real interest

00:01:20.180 --> 00:01:22.910 align:middle line:84%
rate, rather than the nominal
interest rate, which is what

00:01:22.910 --> 00:01:24.980 align:middle line:90%
really controls in practice.

00:01:24.980 --> 00:01:27.530 align:middle line:84%
But I'm going to make that
assumption so the pictures have

00:01:27.530 --> 00:01:29.990 align:middle line:84%
less curves moving
around when things are

00:01:29.990 --> 00:01:33.360 align:middle line:90%
moving when we do the dynamics.

00:01:33.360 --> 00:01:38.120 align:middle line:84%
But that's just a IS-LM,
nothing different.

00:01:38.120 --> 00:01:42.740 align:middle line:84%
And then we look at
the Phillips curve.

00:01:42.740 --> 00:01:47.390 align:middle line:84%
And I said, well, this
is not very useful

00:01:47.390 --> 00:01:53.090 align:middle line:84%
because in the IS part I have
output here and in the Phillips

00:01:53.090 --> 00:01:55.550 align:middle line:84%
curve, I have inflation but
then I have unemployment

00:01:55.550 --> 00:01:58.250 align:middle line:84%
and I don't want to be carrying
around three variables,

00:01:58.250 --> 00:02:01.400 align:middle line:90%
endogenous variables.

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:06.338 align:middle line:84%
And so it's difficult to
diagram in three dimensions.

00:02:06.338 --> 00:02:07.380 align:middle line:90%
Everything is less clear.

00:02:07.380 --> 00:02:13.383 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to replace this
unemployment here for output.

00:02:13.383 --> 00:02:15.800 align:middle line:84%
And it's very easy to do that
with the production function

00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:19.340 align:middle line:84%
we have because output is
just equal to employment.

00:02:19.340 --> 00:02:23.060 align:middle line:84%
And the employment is just
equal to the labor force times 1

00:02:23.060 --> 00:02:24.810 align:middle line:90%
minus the rate of unemployment.

00:02:24.810 --> 00:02:27.800 align:middle line:84%
And we could define a
concept of potential output

00:02:27.800 --> 00:02:30.380 align:middle line:84%
as simply that output that
happens when employment

00:02:30.380 --> 00:02:33.590 align:middle line:84%
is equal to the natural
level of employment, which

00:02:33.590 --> 00:02:35.600 align:middle line:84%
is equal to the
labor force times 1

00:02:35.600 --> 00:02:38.280 align:middle line:84%
minus the natural
rate of unemployment.

00:02:38.280 --> 00:02:40.940 align:middle line:84%
And taking the difference,
subtracting the second line

00:02:40.940 --> 00:02:42.920 align:middle line:84%
from the first one,
you get a concept

00:02:42.920 --> 00:02:45.850 align:middle line:84%
that is used very frequently
in macroeconomics, which is

00:02:45.850 --> 00:02:47.490 align:middle line:90%
the concept of the output gap.

00:02:47.490 --> 00:02:50.870 align:middle line:84%
An output gap refers to the
difference between actual output

00:02:50.870 --> 00:02:53.750 align:middle line:84%
and potential output, in which
potential output is nothing

00:02:53.750 --> 00:02:55.550 align:middle line:84%
else than the level
of output that you

00:02:55.550 --> 00:03:00.390 align:middle line:84%
get when unemployment is at the
natural rate of unemployment.

00:03:00.390 --> 00:03:03.980 align:middle line:84%
So we get the output gap is
related to the employment gap.

00:03:03.980 --> 00:03:07.550 align:middle line:84%
And now we can replace the
employment gap from here

00:03:07.550 --> 00:03:10.670 align:middle line:90%
with the output gap.

00:03:10.670 --> 00:03:12.350 align:middle line:84%
And we end up with
a Phillips curve

00:03:12.350 --> 00:03:14.780 align:middle line:84%
in the space of
inflation and output gap,

00:03:14.780 --> 00:03:17.390 align:middle line:84%
which is something
we can integrate

00:03:17.390 --> 00:03:21.090 align:middle line:84%
very easily with the IS-LM
model that has output in it.

00:03:21.090 --> 00:03:27.320 align:middle line:84%
So the IS-LM model
is really combining

00:03:27.320 --> 00:03:30.140 align:middle line:84%
this equation with
that equation,

00:03:30.140 --> 00:03:32.370 align:middle line:84%
and some model about
expected inflation.

00:03:32.370 --> 00:03:35.860 align:middle line:84%
That's what the
IS-LM-PC model is.

00:03:35.860 --> 00:03:38.780 align:middle line:84%
So I gave you one example
here, 1 mole of inflation.

00:03:38.780 --> 00:03:42.460 align:middle line:84%
This is the case of the
central banks do not like,

00:03:42.460 --> 00:03:44.920 align:middle line:90%
an anchor inflation expectation.

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:47.570 align:middle line:84%
That's my model of expectation,
then my Phillips curve.

00:03:47.570 --> 00:03:49.780 align:middle line:84%
I plug this into
my Phillips curve

00:03:49.780 --> 00:03:53.590 align:middle line:84%
and I get this relationship
between the change in inflation

00:03:53.590 --> 00:03:55.840 align:middle line:90%
and the output gap.

00:03:55.840 --> 00:03:57.530 align:middle line:84%
And it's an increasing
relationship.

00:03:57.530 --> 00:03:59.170 align:middle line:84%
And that's what
I'm plotting here.

00:03:59.170 --> 00:04:03.430 align:middle line:84%
For any given level, for
any given level of Yn,

00:04:03.430 --> 00:04:06.760 align:middle line:84%
then as I increase output,
the Phillips curve--

00:04:06.760 --> 00:04:09.010 align:middle line:84%
the change in inflation,
the left hand side,

00:04:09.010 --> 00:04:12.410 align:middle line:84%
the difference between inflation
and expected inflation rises.

00:04:12.410 --> 00:04:14.110 align:middle line:84%
That's the reason
this upward sloping.

00:04:14.110 --> 00:04:16.839 align:middle line:84%
And the reason this rises has
to do with all the things that

00:04:16.839 --> 00:04:19.480 align:middle line:90%
happen in the labor market.

00:04:19.480 --> 00:04:22.550 align:middle line:84%
If output rises, I mean,
unemployment is falling.

00:04:22.550 --> 00:04:24.680 align:middle line:84%
You need more employment
to produce more output.

00:04:24.680 --> 00:04:26.770 align:middle line:84%
If that's the case,
it's more wage pressure

00:04:26.770 --> 00:04:29.590 align:middle line:84%
that leads to a price
pressure because there

00:04:29.590 --> 00:04:31.850 align:middle line:84%
is a markup in between
wages and prices.

00:04:31.850 --> 00:04:34.880 align:middle line:84%
And that's the way you
get into inflation.

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:38.020 align:middle line:90%
So I gave you one example.

00:04:38.020 --> 00:04:42.940 align:middle line:84%
It says, OK, suppose that
we have some equilibrium

00:04:42.940 --> 00:04:43.810 align:middle line:90%
level of output.

00:04:43.810 --> 00:04:46.840 align:middle line:84%
This, which is the result
of this monetary policy,

00:04:46.840 --> 00:04:51.200 align:middle line:84%
this rate set by
the central bank.

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:54.970 align:middle line:84%
And that's the IS, which is a
function of the fiscal policy

00:04:54.970 --> 00:04:56.980 align:middle line:84%
of the country, how
confident are consumers,

00:04:56.980 --> 00:04:58.310 align:middle line:90%
and all these kind of things.

00:04:58.310 --> 00:05:03.370 align:middle line:84%
So in quiz one, we really worry
only about this top diagram.

00:05:03.370 --> 00:05:05.740 align:middle line:84%
And all the shocks we
had were shocks that

00:05:05.740 --> 00:05:07.400 align:middle line:90%
happened in this top diagram.

00:05:07.400 --> 00:05:10.990 align:middle line:84%
And we look at what happened to
output, to equilibrium output

00:05:10.990 --> 00:05:12.610 align:middle line:90%
as a result.

00:05:12.610 --> 00:05:15.050 align:middle line:90%
Now, this hasn't changed.

00:05:15.050 --> 00:05:16.160 align:middle line:90%
It hasn't changed.

00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:17.990 align:middle line:84%
That block is the
same as it used to be.

00:05:17.990 --> 00:05:20.020 align:middle line:84%
The only difference
that we have here

00:05:20.020 --> 00:05:23.170 align:middle line:84%
is that this level
of output, which

00:05:23.170 --> 00:05:25.780 align:middle line:84%
is the equilibrium level of
output at any point in time,

00:05:25.780 --> 00:05:28.038 align:middle line:84%
needs not be equal
to potential output.

00:05:28.038 --> 00:05:29.830 align:middle line:84%
And if it is not equal
to potential output,

00:05:29.830 --> 00:05:33.010 align:middle line:84%
that will lead to something
with inflation-- inflation,

00:05:33.010 --> 00:05:34.870 align:middle line:84%
disinflation, or
something of that kind.

00:05:34.870 --> 00:05:38.810 align:middle line:84%
In this particular case, the
equilibrium level of output,

00:05:38.810 --> 00:05:41.390 align:middle line:84%
which is still determined
as we used to determine,

00:05:41.390 --> 00:05:45.230 align:middle line:84%
happens to be higher than
the natural rate of output.

00:05:45.230 --> 00:05:48.800 align:middle line:84%
And if output is higher
than the rate of output,

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:52.740 align:middle line:84%
that means this is positive,
which means inflation is rising.

00:05:52.740 --> 00:05:54.620 align:middle line:84%
And that's exactly
what we see here.

00:05:54.620 --> 00:05:57.450 align:middle line:84%
It means inflation is
above expected inflation.

00:05:57.450 --> 00:06:00.170 align:middle line:84%
When expected inflation
is equal to log inflation,

00:06:00.170 --> 00:06:02.900 align:middle line:84%
then that means
inflation is rising.

00:06:02.900 --> 00:06:06.470 align:middle line:90%
And that's what we have here.

00:06:06.470 --> 00:06:08.400 align:middle line:90%
So any question about that?

00:06:08.400 --> 00:06:10.430 align:middle line:84%
So this is-- we
just, what we did

00:06:10.430 --> 00:06:14.540 align:middle line:84%
is kept analysis we used to have
and now we added this diagram

00:06:14.540 --> 00:06:15.590 align:middle line:90%
here at the bottom.

00:06:15.590 --> 00:06:19.010 align:middle line:84%
Because it turns out
that, yes, any equilibrium

00:06:19.010 --> 00:06:21.050 align:middle line:84%
here, if I move the
interest rate around,

00:06:21.050 --> 00:06:22.940 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to change
the level of output.

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:24.900 align:middle line:84%
All those are equilibrium
levels output.

00:06:24.900 --> 00:06:27.440 align:middle line:84%
But that doesn't
mean that they're

00:06:27.440 --> 00:06:29.840 align:middle line:90%
consistent with the natural--

00:06:29.840 --> 00:06:31.160 align:middle line:90%
with potential output.

00:06:31.160 --> 00:06:33.410 align:middle line:84%
And if it's not equal
to potential output,

00:06:33.410 --> 00:06:35.790 align:middle line:84%
it's a valid equilibrium
at any point in time.

00:06:35.790 --> 00:06:39.150 align:middle line:84%
But it's going to lead to
issues on the inflation front.

00:06:39.150 --> 00:06:39.800 align:middle line:90%
That's all.

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:42.380 align:middle line:84%
The second diagram
here tells you

00:06:42.380 --> 00:06:46.070 align:middle line:84%
that we get issues on
the inflation front

00:06:46.070 --> 00:06:49.130 align:middle line:84%
with any equilibrium
level of output that

00:06:49.130 --> 00:06:51.800 align:middle line:84%
is different from the
natural rate of output.

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:53.380 align:middle line:90%
That's what this diagram does.

00:06:53.380 --> 00:06:56.338 align:middle line:90%


00:06:56.338 --> 00:06:57.380 align:middle line:90%
And that's what happened.

00:06:57.380 --> 00:06:58.963 align:middle line:84%
In the short run,
that's what it does.

00:06:58.963 --> 00:07:01.750 align:middle line:84%
So we keep doing what we used to
do in the first seven lectures

00:07:01.750 --> 00:07:02.440 align:middle line:90%
or so.

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:05.890 align:middle line:84%
And this diagram just
tells us what are

00:07:05.890 --> 00:07:07.420 align:middle line:90%
the implications for inflation.

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:08.810 align:middle line:90%
That's in the short run.

00:07:08.810 --> 00:07:12.400 align:middle line:84%
The medium run, we said, is
when we start processing,

00:07:12.400 --> 00:07:16.240 align:middle line:84%
which output converges
back to the natural rate

00:07:16.240 --> 00:07:17.440 align:middle line:90%
to potential output.

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:19.010 align:middle line:90%
How does that happen?

00:07:19.010 --> 00:07:21.700 align:middle line:84%
Well, it involves
the central bank.

00:07:21.700 --> 00:07:24.140 align:middle line:84%
But it's not that the central
bank is doing crazy things.

00:07:24.140 --> 00:07:26.860 align:middle line:84%
The central bank is reacting
to what the economy is

00:07:26.860 --> 00:07:28.340 align:middle line:90%
telling it needs to do.

00:07:28.340 --> 00:07:33.640 align:middle line:84%
Here is a central bank that was
before doing whatever change

00:07:33.640 --> 00:07:36.550 align:middle line:84%
in the interest rate or in the
IS delivered the equilibrium

00:07:36.550 --> 00:07:37.420 align:middle line:90%
output here.

00:07:37.420 --> 00:07:39.440 align:middle line:90%
Had an inflation of around 2%.

00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:41.510 align:middle line:84%
That was consistent
with the target it had.

00:07:41.510 --> 00:07:43.900 align:middle line:84%
Now suddenly it finds itself
in a situation like this

00:07:43.900 --> 00:07:46.510 align:middle line:90%
and inflation starts climbing.

00:07:46.510 --> 00:07:50.840 align:middle line:84%
We get 3% one year,
4%, the next, 6, 9,

00:07:50.840 --> 00:07:52.450 align:middle line:90%
in a situation like that.

00:07:52.450 --> 00:07:54.400 align:middle line:84%
Well, it's very natural
for that central bank,

00:07:54.400 --> 00:07:57.470 align:middle line:84%
if it's a responsible central
bank, to react to that.

00:07:57.470 --> 00:08:00.170 align:middle line:84%
And the only reaction the
central bank can have,

00:08:00.170 --> 00:08:03.120 align:middle line:84%
the main reaction can have,
is to raise interest rates.

00:08:03.120 --> 00:08:05.750 align:middle line:84%
And that's exactly
what starts happening.

00:08:05.750 --> 00:08:08.130 align:middle line:84%
The central bank finds
itself with inflation,

00:08:08.130 --> 00:08:10.260 align:middle line:84%
in this case that
is accelerating.

00:08:10.260 --> 00:08:12.510 align:middle line:84%
It will start increasing
interest rate.

00:08:12.510 --> 00:08:15.980 align:middle line:84%
And this process of acceleration
of inflation in this case

00:08:15.980 --> 00:08:20.090 align:middle line:84%
would only stop when output is
equal to the natural potential

00:08:20.090 --> 00:08:20.790 align:middle line:90%
output.

00:08:20.790 --> 00:08:25.932 align:middle line:84%
And we can define implicitly
what that interest rate is.

00:08:25.932 --> 00:08:28.140 align:middle line:84%
And we can call it the
natural rate of interest rate.

00:08:28.140 --> 00:08:31.310 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes we call
it [INAUDIBLE] rate

00:08:31.310 --> 00:08:35.210 align:middle line:84%
of interest rate, neutral
interest rate, R star,

00:08:35.210 --> 00:08:36.783 align:middle line:84%
lots of names for
this interest rate.

00:08:36.783 --> 00:08:38.450 align:middle line:84%
But this interest
rate is simply the one

00:08:38.450 --> 00:08:41.570 align:middle line:84%
that gives us an equilibrium
output in our IS-LM diagram

00:08:41.570 --> 00:08:45.610 align:middle line:84%
that is equal to
potential output.

00:08:45.610 --> 00:08:47.990 align:middle line:84%
Thus, that's all
that this Rn means.

00:08:47.990 --> 00:08:52.540 align:middle line:84%
And here I'm solving it as the
rate that implicitly gives us

00:08:52.540 --> 00:08:55.150 align:middle line:84%
an equilibrium
output here that is

00:08:55.150 --> 00:08:58.330 align:middle line:84%
equal to the natural rate
of output that defines it

00:08:58.330 --> 00:08:59.690 align:middle line:90%
implicitly.

00:08:59.690 --> 00:09:01.950 align:middle line:90%
OK, there we are.

00:09:01.950 --> 00:09:05.150 align:middle line:90%
Is all that clear?

00:09:05.150 --> 00:09:06.270 align:middle line:90%
Yes, OK.

00:09:06.270 --> 00:09:09.890 align:middle line:84%
I think you're going to have a
big chunk of your current pset

00:09:09.890 --> 00:09:11.670 align:middle line:90%
about this model and so on.

00:09:11.670 --> 00:09:12.990 align:middle line:90%
And that's a good thing.

00:09:12.990 --> 00:09:14.990 align:middle line:84%
And you'll see it
also in the next one.

00:09:14.990 --> 00:09:17.290 align:middle line:84%
Because, again, I think
this is important.

00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:20.110 align:middle line:84%
Then they talk about the
difference between anchor

00:09:20.110 --> 00:09:21.590 align:middle line:90%
and unanchor expectations.

00:09:21.590 --> 00:09:24.670 align:middle line:84%
I said, look, here,
we have a situation

00:09:24.670 --> 00:09:26.690 align:middle line:90%
that suppose we started at 2%.

00:09:26.690 --> 00:09:29.570 align:middle line:84%
And then we found ourselves
in a situation like that.

00:09:29.570 --> 00:09:32.120 align:middle line:84%
That means inflation
starts building up.

00:09:32.120 --> 00:09:33.920 align:middle line:90%
We go to 9% or so.

00:09:33.920 --> 00:09:36.010 align:middle line:84%
So now the Fed
gets scared and it

00:09:36.010 --> 00:09:37.460 align:middle line:90%
starts raising interest rates.

00:09:37.460 --> 00:09:39.680 align:middle line:84%
So that's moving
up, lowering output.

00:09:39.680 --> 00:09:42.430 align:middle line:84%
And as it lowers output,
reduces the output gap.

00:09:42.430 --> 00:09:46.370 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, reduces the
change in inflation here.

00:09:46.370 --> 00:09:49.360 align:middle line:84%
But inflation keeps rising
in this particular model

00:09:49.360 --> 00:09:51.590 align:middle line:84%
because expected
inflation is an anchor.

00:09:51.590 --> 00:09:54.100 align:middle line:84%
And I said, well, suppose
that eventually the Fed gets

00:09:54.100 --> 00:09:55.900 align:middle line:90%
to that interest rate here.

00:09:55.900 --> 00:09:58.030 align:middle line:84%
So we get to a
situation like that.

00:09:58.030 --> 00:10:02.170 align:middle line:84%
And I ask the question, has
the Fed solved the problem now?

00:10:02.170 --> 00:10:03.790 align:middle line:84%
OK, finally we
get to a situation

00:10:03.790 --> 00:10:07.300 align:middle line:84%
where the interest rate is equal
to the natural rate of interest

00:10:07.300 --> 00:10:07.850 align:middle line:90%
rate.

00:10:07.850 --> 00:10:10.490 align:middle line:84%
That tells me that output is
equal to potential output.

00:10:10.490 --> 00:10:13.180 align:middle line:84%
That tells me here that
inflation is not changing.

00:10:13.180 --> 00:10:17.940 align:middle line:84%
Problem is that we already had
inflation of 9% at some point.

00:10:17.940 --> 00:10:22.040 align:middle line:84%
So here, inflation stops
rising in this particular model

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:25.320 align:middle line:84%
with expected inflation and
anchor expected inflation.

00:10:25.320 --> 00:10:28.910 align:middle line:84%
But stopping is not enough
because that leaves us

00:10:28.910 --> 00:10:31.370 align:middle line:90%
with a level of inflation of 9%.

00:10:31.370 --> 00:10:34.670 align:middle line:84%
That means that the Fed, in
order to bring back inflation

00:10:34.670 --> 00:10:38.180 align:middle line:84%
to 2%, it needs to
go into this region.

00:10:38.180 --> 00:10:44.490 align:middle line:84%
So inflation starts coming down
from 9%, 7%, 6%, 5% and so on.

00:10:44.490 --> 00:10:47.630 align:middle line:84%
So if you have an
anchor expectation,

00:10:47.630 --> 00:10:50.060 align:middle line:84%
an inflation
overshoots, you're going

00:10:50.060 --> 00:10:53.160 align:middle line:84%
to have to cause a recession,
and probably a severe recession.

00:10:53.160 --> 00:10:54.680 align:middle line:90%
There is no way around that.

00:10:54.680 --> 00:10:57.470 align:middle line:84%
And that's what the Fed
has been struggling to do,

00:10:57.470 --> 00:10:58.760 align:middle line:90%
is struggling not to.

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:01.670 align:middle line:84%
Because the Fed, we are in a
situation-- not only in the US,

00:11:01.670 --> 00:11:04.340 align:middle line:84%
but in the US in
particular, where inflation

00:11:04.340 --> 00:11:06.830 align:middle line:90%
is way above the target level.

00:11:06.830 --> 00:11:10.530 align:middle line:84%
But expected inflation has
been more or less stable.

00:11:10.530 --> 00:11:13.160 align:middle line:84%
And so when people
talk about being

00:11:13.160 --> 00:11:17.870 align:middle line:84%
able to restore sort of
reasonable levels of inflation

00:11:17.870 --> 00:11:21.020 align:middle line:84%
in a soft landed manner,
with a soft landing,

00:11:21.020 --> 00:11:24.710 align:middle line:84%
that means that you don't
need to cause a recession

00:11:24.710 --> 00:11:27.150 align:middle line:90%
to bring inflation back to 2%.

00:11:27.150 --> 00:11:29.150 align:middle line:84%
You just can bring
it smoothly here.

00:11:29.150 --> 00:11:31.860 align:middle line:84%
With this model of expected,
inflation doesn't work.

00:11:31.860 --> 00:11:36.800 align:middle line:84%
But if the bank, central bank,
has credibility and inflation

00:11:36.800 --> 00:11:39.410 align:middle line:84%
remain anchored, people continue
to believe that the Fed will

00:11:39.410 --> 00:11:40.730 align:middle line:90%
go back to 2%.

00:11:40.730 --> 00:11:42.750 align:middle line:84%
Then you don't need to
cause a big recession.

00:11:42.750 --> 00:11:46.220 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, you need to invest
in bringing expectations down.

00:11:46.220 --> 00:11:48.200 align:middle line:84%
And the only way you
can invest in doing that

00:11:48.200 --> 00:11:49.760 align:middle line:90%
is causing a recession.

00:11:49.760 --> 00:11:53.450 align:middle line:84%
But that's the reason I said
central banks worry so much

00:11:53.450 --> 00:11:56.090 align:middle line:84%
about keeping
inflation credibility,

00:11:56.090 --> 00:11:59.420 align:middle line:84%
because otherwise they
need to overshoot in order

00:11:59.420 --> 00:12:06.140 align:middle line:90%
to restore a long run balance.

00:12:06.140 --> 00:12:08.550 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:12:08.550 --> 00:12:14.780 align:middle line:84%
Now, you may wonder, well, I
mean, this looks pretty simple.

00:12:14.780 --> 00:12:16.700 align:middle line:84%
And just, if you have
a problem like this,

00:12:16.700 --> 00:12:21.020 align:middle line:84%
just go quickly to
that point there.

00:12:21.020 --> 00:12:22.590 align:middle line:90%
And then the problem is over.

00:12:22.590 --> 00:12:26.340 align:middle line:84%
You don't let inflation build
to 9%, or something like that.

00:12:26.340 --> 00:12:27.650 align:middle line:90%
You react immediately.

00:12:27.650 --> 00:12:30.380 align:middle line:84%
The problem is, there's
a famous sentence that

00:12:30.380 --> 00:12:32.990 align:middle line:84%
was coined by
Milton Friedman, is

00:12:32.990 --> 00:12:34.940 align:middle line:84%
that monetary policy
acts on the economy

00:12:34.940 --> 00:12:37.100 align:middle line:90%
with long and variable lags.

00:12:37.100 --> 00:12:40.580 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, it's very
difficult at any point in time

00:12:40.580 --> 00:12:42.710 align:middle line:84%
to know where is
potential output

00:12:42.710 --> 00:12:44.640 align:middle line:84%
and what is a natural
rate of unemployment.

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:45.890 align:middle line:90%
I mean, you sort of sense it.

00:12:45.890 --> 00:12:48.560 align:middle line:84%
But the truth is that the
only way you really know

00:12:48.560 --> 00:12:50.610 align:middle line:90%
is by looking at inflation.

00:12:50.610 --> 00:12:52.880 align:middle line:84%
So it's inflation that
really tells you that you

00:12:52.880 --> 00:12:54.330 align:middle line:90%
are on one side or the other.

00:12:54.330 --> 00:12:56.150 align:middle line:90%
It's very difficult to--

00:12:56.150 --> 00:12:58.470 align:middle line:84%
you have some historical
average and so on.

00:12:58.470 --> 00:12:59.812 align:middle line:90%
But these things do move around.

00:12:59.812 --> 00:13:01.520 align:middle line:84%
So it's difficult to
at any point in time

00:13:01.520 --> 00:13:05.670 align:middle line:84%
to know whether you
are at our end or not.

00:13:05.670 --> 00:13:09.740 align:middle line:84%
The second thing is that here
everything happens immediately.

00:13:09.740 --> 00:13:12.540 align:middle line:84%
If I move immediately, then
output immediately jumps here.

00:13:12.540 --> 00:13:15.060 align:middle line:84%
That's not the way monetary
policy operates in practice.

00:13:15.060 --> 00:13:19.710 align:middle line:84%
It takes time for monetary
policy to affect the economy.

00:13:19.710 --> 00:13:24.620 align:middle line:84%
And so the situation that
happened, I would say,

00:13:24.620 --> 00:13:28.610 align:middle line:84%
until last week, was the
Fed knew that the inflation

00:13:28.610 --> 00:13:30.400 align:middle line:90%
was still too high.

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:32.810 align:middle line:84%
But it also knew that
it had done a lot.

00:13:32.810 --> 00:13:35.360 align:middle line:84%
It had hiked rates very
aggressively by a lot.

00:13:35.360 --> 00:13:40.090 align:middle line:84%
And since there are lags between
the increase in interest rate

00:13:40.090 --> 00:13:43.720 align:middle line:84%
and the decline in
output, the Fed's concern

00:13:43.720 --> 00:13:46.390 align:middle line:84%
was, well, it's clear that
I still have inflation.

00:13:46.390 --> 00:13:48.850 align:middle line:84%
But it may well be the case
that when this thing finally

00:13:48.850 --> 00:13:51.370 align:middle line:84%
hits the economy,
it hits it too much

00:13:51.370 --> 00:13:54.410 align:middle line:84%
and we end up in a recession,
and an unwanted recession.

00:13:54.410 --> 00:13:57.550 align:middle line:90%
That was the concern.

00:13:57.550 --> 00:13:59.313 align:middle line:84%
Now, what is
happening right now,

00:13:59.313 --> 00:14:00.730 align:middle line:84%
there is a little
bit of a concern

00:14:00.730 --> 00:14:03.100 align:middle line:84%
that we got to that point
because things were very

00:14:03.100 --> 00:14:04.880 align:middle line:90%
slow for a variety of reasons.

00:14:04.880 --> 00:14:06.820 align:middle line:90%
But now something broke.

00:14:06.820 --> 00:14:10.510 align:middle line:84%
And the question is, now
that something has broken,

00:14:10.510 --> 00:14:13.930 align:middle line:84%
will we sort of decelerate
the economy very, very fast?

00:14:13.930 --> 00:14:15.010 align:middle line:90%
And that's a concern.

00:14:15.010 --> 00:14:16.630 align:middle line:84%
That's what is
happening right now.

00:14:16.630 --> 00:14:20.780 align:middle line:84%
But that's what makes monetary
policy much more difficult

00:14:20.780 --> 00:14:22.610 align:middle line:84%
than this little
diagram, is that you

00:14:22.610 --> 00:14:25.400 align:middle line:84%
have all these lags, these
uncertainties, and all

00:14:25.400 --> 00:14:26.540 align:middle line:90%
these non-linearities.

00:14:26.540 --> 00:14:28.180 align:middle line:90%
And suddenly things happen.

00:14:28.180 --> 00:14:31.820 align:middle line:90%


00:14:31.820 --> 00:14:35.010 align:middle line:84%
Let me tell you when things
can go really, really wrong.

00:14:35.010 --> 00:14:36.630 align:middle line:90%
It's not the issue now.

00:14:36.630 --> 00:14:40.890 align:middle line:84%
But we were very close to that
during the global recession.

00:14:40.890 --> 00:14:42.560 align:middle line:84%
Japan has experienced
several episodes

00:14:42.560 --> 00:14:44.760 align:middle line:84%
like this, which
is the following.

00:14:44.760 --> 00:14:50.747 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you have a situation
where your inflation is low.

00:14:50.747 --> 00:14:52.580 align:middle line:84%
Typically, these things
happen in situations

00:14:52.580 --> 00:14:54.600 align:middle line:90%
where inflation is low.

00:14:54.600 --> 00:14:58.650 align:middle line:84%
And for whatever reason, your
natural rate of unemployment

00:14:58.650 --> 00:15:00.820 align:middle line:90%
is negative.

00:15:00.820 --> 00:15:03.940 align:middle line:84%
So you have inflation
close to 0, say.

00:15:03.940 --> 00:15:09.150 align:middle line:84%
And then the natural rate of
interest rate is negative.

00:15:09.150 --> 00:15:10.530 align:middle line:90%
What's the problem?

00:15:10.530 --> 00:15:13.230 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you have
a 0 lower bound.

00:15:13.230 --> 00:15:15.090 align:middle line:84%
Well, you have a 0
lower bound means

00:15:15.090 --> 00:15:18.430 align:middle line:84%
that you're not going
to hit this rate.

00:15:18.430 --> 00:15:20.797 align:middle line:84%
The best you can do with
inflation is around 0.

00:15:20.797 --> 00:15:22.630 align:middle line:84%
Then you set the nominal
interest rate to 0.

00:15:22.630 --> 00:15:25.620 align:middle line:84%
And then the real
interest rate is around 0.

00:15:25.620 --> 00:15:34.330 align:middle line:84%
Well, the problem is that at 0,
you generate negative inflation.

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:36.850 align:middle line:84%
But if you generate
negative inflation

00:15:36.850 --> 00:15:40.060 align:middle line:84%
and the nominal interest
rate is fixed at 0, then

00:15:40.060 --> 00:15:42.280 align:middle line:84%
now you get a positive
real interest rate

00:15:42.280 --> 00:15:44.980 align:middle line:84%
because the real interest rate
is equal to the nominal interest

00:15:44.980 --> 00:15:49.400 align:middle line:84%
rate, which is 0, minus
inflation, expected inflation.

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:52.960 align:middle line:84%
But if your expected inflation
or inflation is negative,

00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:54.530 align:middle line:90%
minus, minus is positive.

00:15:54.530 --> 00:15:57.610 align:middle line:84%
So that means your real interest
rate is actually positive.

00:15:57.610 --> 00:16:00.190 align:middle line:84%
So you wanted
something negative.

00:16:00.190 --> 00:16:02.980 align:middle line:84%
But you end up with
something positive.

00:16:02.980 --> 00:16:06.300 align:middle line:84%
That means now you
have a big gap here.

00:16:06.300 --> 00:16:09.760 align:middle line:84%
So inflation, you
get into deflation.

00:16:09.760 --> 00:16:11.630 align:middle line:90%
Now inflation is very, very low.

00:16:11.630 --> 00:16:12.970 align:middle line:90%
It gets very negative.

00:16:12.970 --> 00:16:16.290 align:middle line:84%
Well, as inflation gets
more and more negative,

00:16:16.290 --> 00:16:18.220 align:middle line:84%
your real interest
rate keeps climbing.

00:16:18.220 --> 00:16:20.370 align:middle line:84%
So you keep moving
further and further away

00:16:20.370 --> 00:16:23.730 align:middle line:84%
from the natural rate
of interest rate.

00:16:23.730 --> 00:16:26.730 align:middle line:84%
Thus, something that is
very scary for an economist,

00:16:26.730 --> 00:16:29.010 align:middle line:90%
that deflationary trap.

00:16:29.010 --> 00:16:33.100 align:middle line:84%
And that's the way you
get into deep recessions.

00:16:33.100 --> 00:16:36.090 align:middle line:84%
In fact, that's what happened
during the Great Recession

00:16:36.090 --> 00:16:37.800 align:middle line:90%
in the US.

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:42.850 align:middle line:84%
The no, during the Great
Depression in the US.

00:16:42.850 --> 00:16:44.850 align:middle line:84%
During the Great Recession,
we were close to it,

00:16:44.850 --> 00:16:48.690 align:middle line:84%
but we didn't get quite
there because lots of things

00:16:48.690 --> 00:16:54.000 align:middle line:84%
were done to prevent a repeat
of the Great Depression.

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:57.450 align:middle line:84%
One of the biggest problems
with the Great Depression

00:16:57.450 --> 00:17:02.610 align:middle line:84%
was that monetary policy was
not against the 0 lower bound.

00:17:02.610 --> 00:17:05.650 align:middle line:90%
But it was very slow to react.

00:17:05.650 --> 00:17:08.840 align:middle line:84%
They were in a situation
like in this diagram here.

00:17:08.840 --> 00:17:11.720 align:middle line:90%


00:17:11.720 --> 00:17:14.000 align:middle line:84%
But they kept the
interest rate high.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:15.920 align:middle line:90%
And they moved very slowly.

00:17:15.920 --> 00:17:18.740 align:middle line:84%
And when they tried to
catch up, well, they

00:17:18.740 --> 00:17:20.550 align:middle line:84%
went into deflationary
environment.

00:17:20.550 --> 00:17:22.970 align:middle line:84%
So the real interest rate
was moving away from them,

00:17:22.970 --> 00:17:25.428 align:middle line:84%
despite the fact that they were
moving the nominal interest

00:17:25.428 --> 00:17:26.240 align:middle line:90%
rate down.

00:17:26.240 --> 00:17:27.960 align:middle line:90%
And that you can see here.

00:17:27.960 --> 00:17:31.460 align:middle line:84%
So the Great Depression
starts around 1929.

00:17:31.460 --> 00:17:34.160 align:middle line:90%
It starts really in 1929.

00:17:34.160 --> 00:17:36.350 align:middle line:90%
Unemployment initially was low.

00:17:36.350 --> 00:17:39.110 align:middle line:84%
The nominal interest
rate was around 5%.

00:17:39.110 --> 00:17:42.860 align:middle line:84%
And inflation rate, growth
declined very rapidly.

00:17:42.860 --> 00:17:45.090 align:middle line:90%
The inflation rate was around 0.

00:17:45.090 --> 00:17:46.520 align:middle line:90%
So you had a one year--

00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:50.300 align:middle line:84%
the real interest rate
was around 5%, as well.

00:17:50.300 --> 00:17:53.040 align:middle line:90%
Well, things got worse.

00:17:53.040 --> 00:17:55.710 align:middle line:84%
Unemployment began to
climb very rapidly.

00:17:55.710 --> 00:17:59.630 align:middle line:84%
And so the Fed began to lower
interest rates, nominal interest

00:17:59.630 --> 00:18:00.470 align:middle line:90%
rate.

00:18:00.470 --> 00:18:02.130 align:middle line:90%
Went from 5% to 4%.

00:18:02.130 --> 00:18:06.030 align:middle line:84%
Those were unusually low
interest rates for the time.

00:18:06.030 --> 00:18:10.880 align:middle line:84%
But the problem is that the
inflation by then was -2.5%.

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:12.987 align:middle line:84%
So the real interest
rate-- they were lowering

00:18:12.987 --> 00:18:14.070 align:middle line:90%
the nominal interest rate.

00:18:14.070 --> 00:18:16.600 align:middle line:84%
But the real interest
rate was rising.

00:18:16.600 --> 00:18:20.560 align:middle line:84%
And unemployment, accordingly,
was rising, as well.

00:18:20.560 --> 00:18:22.720 align:middle line:90%
It kept going.

00:18:22.720 --> 00:18:27.200 align:middle line:84%
Then they began to cut the
interest rate more aggressively.

00:18:27.200 --> 00:18:31.010 align:middle line:84%
But we got into real
deflation, -10% or so.

00:18:31.010 --> 00:18:34.200 align:middle line:84%
So the real interest
rate kept climbing.

00:18:34.200 --> 00:18:39.240 align:middle line:84%
At that point was a very
poor time interest rate hike,

00:18:39.240 --> 00:18:43.170 align:middle line:84%
was a disaster for
unemployment because it really

00:18:43.170 --> 00:18:45.510 align:middle line:84%
hiked the interest rate, real
interest rates even more.

00:18:45.510 --> 00:18:47.790 align:middle line:84%
And eventually got
out of it with a bunch

00:18:47.790 --> 00:18:49.840 align:middle line:84%
of policies that were
non-monetary policies.

00:18:49.840 --> 00:18:53.590 align:middle line:90%
But that's what happened.

00:18:53.590 --> 00:18:55.470 align:middle line:84%
So the Great Depression
was very much

00:18:55.470 --> 00:19:01.110 align:middle line:84%
a story of this kind
in which essentially we

00:19:01.110 --> 00:19:04.740 align:middle line:84%
fell into depression so that
interest rate began to climb

00:19:04.740 --> 00:19:07.740 align:middle line:84%
and got the economy deeper
and deeper into recession

00:19:07.740 --> 00:19:09.640 align:middle line:84%
and unemployment higher
and higher and so on.

00:19:09.640 --> 00:19:12.090 align:middle line:84%
And at some point, monetary
policy just didn't work.

00:19:12.090 --> 00:19:14.340 align:middle line:84%
So that's the reason you
have to essentially do

00:19:14.340 --> 00:19:16.720 align:middle line:84%
massive fiscal policy
to get out of it.

00:19:16.720 --> 00:19:20.970 align:middle line:90%


00:19:20.970 --> 00:19:22.500 align:middle line:84%
Let me talk about
some of the shocks

00:19:22.500 --> 00:19:26.940 align:middle line:84%
we have discussed in the context
of this more complete model now.

00:19:26.940 --> 00:19:33.280 align:middle line:84%
And actually-- OK, let me talk
about two canonical type shocks.

00:19:33.280 --> 00:19:36.960 align:middle line:84%
You can have two broad
type of shocks or policies

00:19:36.960 --> 00:19:41.070 align:middle line:84%
in these models that
you want to analyze.

00:19:41.070 --> 00:19:43.530 align:middle line:84%
Some of them are aggregate
demand, either policies

00:19:43.530 --> 00:19:44.700 align:middle line:90%
or shocks or whatever.

00:19:44.700 --> 00:19:46.470 align:middle line:90%
Those are things that you know.

00:19:46.470 --> 00:19:50.440 align:middle line:84%
Aggregate demand policies
move the IS curve--

00:19:50.440 --> 00:19:55.380 align:middle line:84%
IS and LM, but moves
operates in the goods market.

00:19:55.380 --> 00:19:59.760 align:middle line:84%
So this is one case of a
contractionary fiscal policy,

00:19:59.760 --> 00:20:01.390 align:middle line:90%
a fiscal consolidation.

00:20:01.390 --> 00:20:02.590 align:middle line:90%
So what happens here?

00:20:02.590 --> 00:20:06.060 align:middle line:84%
Suppose you start an
equilibrium level of output

00:20:06.060 --> 00:20:07.560 align:middle line:84%
equal to the natural
rate of output.

00:20:07.560 --> 00:20:08.820 align:middle line:84%
But now, for whatever
reason, we're

00:20:08.820 --> 00:20:10.510 align:middle line:84%
running deficits
that are very large.

00:20:10.510 --> 00:20:12.910 align:middle line:84%
You want to reduce the
size of the deficit.

00:20:12.910 --> 00:20:14.850 align:middle line:84%
Well, you move the
IS to the left.

00:20:14.850 --> 00:20:16.530 align:middle line:84%
Now you cut government
expenditure.

00:20:16.530 --> 00:20:17.770 align:middle line:90%
You increase taxes.

00:20:17.770 --> 00:20:21.010 align:middle line:84%
That will bring output below
the natural rate of output.

00:20:21.010 --> 00:20:22.780 align:middle line:84%
You go to the
Phillips curve here.

00:20:22.780 --> 00:20:26.160 align:middle line:84%
That means inflation now, you
get into the deflationary forces

00:20:26.160 --> 00:20:28.170 align:middle line:90%
or inflation starts declining.

00:20:28.170 --> 00:20:29.762 align:middle line:90%
The result of that--

00:20:29.762 --> 00:20:31.470 align:middle line:84%
So in the short run,
you get exactly what

00:20:31.470 --> 00:20:34.020 align:middle line:84%
we had in lecture
five, six or whatever.

00:20:34.020 --> 00:20:36.190 align:middle line:84%
You get a contraction
in real output.

00:20:36.190 --> 00:20:39.180 align:middle line:84%
But on top of that, you
start getting inflation

00:20:39.180 --> 00:20:41.380 align:middle line:84%
coming down, or
even going negative.

00:20:41.380 --> 00:20:44.910 align:middle line:84%
And as a result of that,
the central bank will react.

00:20:44.910 --> 00:20:46.140 align:middle line:90%
And it will react.

00:20:46.140 --> 00:20:49.080 align:middle line:84%
And that reaction will
stop when in the long run

00:20:49.080 --> 00:20:52.110 align:middle line:84%
when output goes back to
the initial level of output,

00:20:52.110 --> 00:20:53.500 align:middle line:90%
its natural rate of output.

00:20:53.500 --> 00:20:56.940 align:middle line:84%
So the point of
this picture that

00:20:56.940 --> 00:20:59.040 align:middle line:84%
is new relative to
things you already knew

00:20:59.040 --> 00:21:01.830 align:middle line:84%
is that in the short run,
you get very much the type

00:21:01.830 --> 00:21:03.850 align:middle line:90%
of responses we had early on.

00:21:03.850 --> 00:21:07.680 align:middle line:84%
In the medium run, in the
medium run, you don't get that.

00:21:07.680 --> 00:21:10.950 align:middle line:84%
A fiscal consolidation does not
reduce output in the medium run.

00:21:10.950 --> 00:21:15.270 align:middle line:84%
The fiscal consolidation does is
reduces the real interest rate

00:21:15.270 --> 00:21:17.320 align:middle line:90%
in the medium run.

00:21:17.320 --> 00:21:19.890 align:middle line:84%
So you see here,
output eventually

00:21:19.890 --> 00:21:24.130 align:middle line:84%
goes back to that level with a
much lower real interest rate.

00:21:24.130 --> 00:21:26.670 align:middle line:90%


00:21:26.670 --> 00:21:30.480 align:middle line:84%
The point is
sometimes this path,

00:21:30.480 --> 00:21:33.650 align:middle line:84%
this path takes your output down
initially and then comes back,

00:21:33.650 --> 00:21:34.810 align:middle line:90%
can be very painful.

00:21:34.810 --> 00:21:38.200 align:middle line:84%
It can take a long time to
generate a procession and so on.

00:21:38.200 --> 00:21:41.670 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes it can happen
in any sort of conditions

00:21:41.670 --> 00:21:43.190 align:middle line:90%
and be faster and so on.

00:21:43.190 --> 00:21:46.560 align:middle line:84%
Many of the policies,
agreements that people have,

00:21:46.560 --> 00:21:48.900 align:middle line:84%
people that understand
what they're talking about,

00:21:48.900 --> 00:21:51.550 align:middle line:84%
had to do with the speed at
which these things happen.

00:21:51.550 --> 00:21:53.790 align:middle line:84%
So sometimes people
can agree that you

00:21:53.790 --> 00:21:54.960 align:middle line:90%
need a fiscal consolidation.

00:21:54.960 --> 00:21:57.880 align:middle line:84%
But someone may think, no, this
stuff is going to be very slow.

00:21:57.880 --> 00:22:00.713 align:middle line:84%
And so I don't want to incur in
a very deep recession for very

00:22:00.713 --> 00:22:02.880 align:middle line:84%
long just to adjust a little
bit the fiscal deficit.

00:22:02.880 --> 00:22:05.070 align:middle line:84%
And others may
think the opposite.

00:22:05.070 --> 00:22:06.660 align:middle line:90%
It's mostly about the speed.

00:22:06.660 --> 00:22:10.590 align:middle line:84%
But shorter response to
a fiscal consolidation

00:22:10.590 --> 00:22:12.270 align:middle line:84%
or to any aggregate
demand contraction

00:22:12.270 --> 00:22:15.523 align:middle line:84%
is different than the
medium term response.

00:22:15.523 --> 00:22:19.110 align:middle line:90%


00:22:19.110 --> 00:22:21.480 align:middle line:84%
And again, the signals
for the central bank

00:22:21.480 --> 00:22:22.980 align:middle line:84%
that it needs to
move interest rate,

00:22:22.980 --> 00:22:25.630 align:middle line:84%
they all come from this block
here-- inflation falling.

00:22:25.630 --> 00:22:27.990 align:middle line:84%
That tells the
central bank, oops,

00:22:27.990 --> 00:22:30.910 align:middle line:84%
we may have a
problem, and so on.

00:22:30.910 --> 00:22:35.290 align:middle line:84%
Another kind of shock
that is more complicated

00:22:35.290 --> 00:22:37.300 align:middle line:84%
and that has played
a role actually

00:22:37.300 --> 00:22:39.400 align:middle line:84%
very much in the
recovery from COVID

00:22:39.400 --> 00:22:42.040 align:middle line:84%
is some sort of
supply side shock--

00:22:42.040 --> 00:22:44.230 align:middle line:90%
for example, an oil shock.

00:22:44.230 --> 00:22:47.090 align:middle line:84%
The price of energy goes
up or something like that.

00:22:47.090 --> 00:22:50.630 align:middle line:84%
Well, that one, how
do you analyze that?

00:22:50.630 --> 00:22:53.180 align:middle line:84%
A supply side shock is not
something that comes from,

00:22:53.180 --> 00:22:56.900 align:middle line:84%
that would go to the
IS-LM part of the model.

00:22:56.900 --> 00:22:58.550 align:middle line:84%
A supply side
shock, remember, we

00:22:58.550 --> 00:23:02.690 align:middle line:84%
analyze it when we analyze the
natural rate of unemployment.

00:23:02.690 --> 00:23:05.600 align:middle line:84%
It's something that affects
the supply side of the economy.

00:23:05.600 --> 00:23:09.200 align:middle line:84%
We can model that as an
increase in the markup.

00:23:09.200 --> 00:23:11.810 align:middle line:84%
And we know that an
increase in the markup

00:23:11.810 --> 00:23:14.930 align:middle line:84%
will increase the natural
rate of unemployment.

00:23:14.930 --> 00:23:21.130 align:middle line:84%
That means that this shock will
do what to potential output?

00:23:21.130 --> 00:23:25.150 align:middle line:90%


00:23:25.150 --> 00:23:29.350 align:middle line:84%
So an energy shock, especially
if it's a persistent one,

00:23:29.350 --> 00:23:32.080 align:middle line:84%
will operate like
a markup shock.

00:23:32.080 --> 00:23:35.980 align:middle line:84%
And that we know will
increase the natural rate

00:23:35.980 --> 00:23:37.510 align:middle line:90%
of unemployment.

00:23:37.510 --> 00:23:42.290 align:middle line:84%
So what happens to
the potential output?

00:23:42.290 --> 00:23:44.690 align:middle line:90%
Goes down, of course.

00:23:44.690 --> 00:23:47.052 align:middle line:84%
Output is equal to
employment, to labor force

00:23:47.052 --> 00:23:49.010 align:middle line:84%
times 1 minus the natural
rate of unemployment.

00:23:49.010 --> 00:23:50.843 align:middle line:84%
If the natural rate of
unemployment goes up,

00:23:50.843 --> 00:23:53.000 align:middle line:84%
then the potential
output goes down.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:23:55.950 align:middle line:84%
So that is not a shift
in the top diagram.

00:23:55.950 --> 00:23:57.740 align:middle line:84%
It's a shift in
the lower diagram.

00:23:57.740 --> 00:24:00.840 align:middle line:84%
It says, we used to have
this Phillips curve.

00:24:00.840 --> 00:24:04.560 align:middle line:84%
And now the Phillips curve
has shifted to the left.

00:24:04.560 --> 00:24:07.243 align:middle line:84%
Because we have a new
natural rate of an output.

00:24:07.243 --> 00:24:08.910 align:middle line:84%
And remember, the
natural rate of output

00:24:08.910 --> 00:24:14.630 align:middle line:84%
is at that point when output
equal to the natural rate

00:24:14.630 --> 00:24:19.620 align:middle line:84%
of output does not produce
inflationary forces.

00:24:19.620 --> 00:24:21.500 align:middle line:84%
What happened with
this shock here?

00:24:21.500 --> 00:24:24.240 align:middle line:84%
So suppose the economy was
in this equilibrium here

00:24:24.240 --> 00:24:29.110 align:middle line:84%
and now it gets hit
by an oil shock.

00:24:29.110 --> 00:24:31.150 align:middle line:84%
In the short run,
if no one reacts,

00:24:31.150 --> 00:24:33.410 align:middle line:90%
nothing happens to output.

00:24:33.410 --> 00:24:34.730 align:middle line:90%
Doesn't move much.

00:24:34.730 --> 00:24:35.725 align:middle line:90%
But what happens?

00:24:35.725 --> 00:24:42.440 align:middle line:90%


00:24:42.440 --> 00:24:44.240 align:middle line:84%
You see, if I don't
move something

00:24:44.240 --> 00:24:47.310 align:middle line:84%
in this part of the diagram, I'm
not moving equilibrium output.

00:24:47.310 --> 00:24:48.920 align:middle line:84%
In the short run,
equilibrium output

00:24:48.920 --> 00:24:50.480 align:middle line:84%
is determined exactly
in the same way

00:24:50.480 --> 00:24:52.100 align:middle line:90%
we have determined up to now.

00:24:52.100 --> 00:24:57.980 align:middle line:84%
So if we get a markup shock,
nothing happens to output.

00:24:57.980 --> 00:25:02.150 align:middle line:84%
If nobody moves, nothing happens
to output in the short run.

00:25:02.150 --> 00:25:07.590 align:middle line:84%
But what happens
that we may not like?

00:25:07.590 --> 00:25:08.670 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:25:08.670 --> 00:25:09.790 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:25:09.790 --> 00:25:11.970 align:middle line:84%
What happens is the
Phillips curve went up.

00:25:11.970 --> 00:25:16.410 align:middle line:84%
Before, that level of output
was consistent with no changes

00:25:16.410 --> 00:25:17.580 align:middle line:90%
in inflation.

00:25:17.580 --> 00:25:19.320 align:middle line:90%
Now, it's not.

00:25:19.320 --> 00:25:21.640 align:middle line:90%
We get an increase in inflation.

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:27.210 align:middle line:84%
So the first place where you'll
see the effect of the oil shock

00:25:27.210 --> 00:25:28.617 align:middle line:90%
here is inflation will pick up.

00:25:28.617 --> 00:25:31.200 align:middle line:84%
Remember, the price of gasoline
going up and all those things.

00:25:31.200 --> 00:25:33.180 align:middle line:84%
Well, that's where
you see it first.

00:25:33.180 --> 00:25:36.000 align:middle line:84%
Before activity falls,
you see it there.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:38.190 align:middle line:84%
That's what makes up
the Phillips curve also,

00:25:38.190 --> 00:25:39.480 align:middle line:90%
in the '70s and '80s.

00:25:39.480 --> 00:25:41.820 align:middle line:84%
You can see lots of
shocks of this kind.

00:25:41.820 --> 00:25:44.310 align:middle line:84%
Initially, unemployment
didn't move much,

00:25:44.310 --> 00:25:47.190 align:middle line:90%
but inflation kept climbing.

00:25:47.190 --> 00:25:48.252 align:middle line:90%
So that's what happens.

00:25:48.252 --> 00:25:49.710 align:middle line:84%
Well, obviously,
when that happens,

00:25:49.710 --> 00:25:51.593 align:middle line:84%
if it persists-- and
typically central banks,

00:25:51.593 --> 00:25:53.010 align:middle line:84%
if they think is
very short lived,

00:25:53.010 --> 00:25:54.718 align:middle line:84%
they're not going to
react to this stuff.

00:25:54.718 --> 00:25:57.420 align:middle line:84%
But if it is persistent and
they think it's persistent,

00:25:57.420 --> 00:25:59.540 align:middle line:90%
then the reaction is what?

00:25:59.540 --> 00:26:00.820 align:middle line:90%
Well, they need to--

00:26:00.820 --> 00:26:06.210 align:middle line:84%
this only means that the
natural rate of interest

00:26:06.210 --> 00:26:09.960 align:middle line:84%
has gone up because I
need, for that same IS,

00:26:09.960 --> 00:26:12.510 align:middle line:84%
I need to bring down
equilibrium output.

00:26:12.510 --> 00:26:16.230 align:middle line:84%
That means I need a higher
natural rate of interest rate,

00:26:16.230 --> 00:26:17.893 align:middle line:90%
or a higher R star.

00:26:17.893 --> 00:26:20.310 align:middle line:84%
So what the Fed needs to do,
the central bank needs to do,

00:26:20.310 --> 00:26:22.250 align:middle line:84%
is just start increasing
interest rates.

00:26:22.250 --> 00:26:24.620 align:middle line:90%
That's a natural response.

00:26:24.620 --> 00:26:26.300 align:middle line:84%
A lot of what happened
during the COVID,

00:26:26.300 --> 00:26:29.150 align:middle line:84%
why inflation picked
up so much in COVID

00:26:29.150 --> 00:26:31.970 align:middle line:84%
is because we had a
shock of this kind.

00:26:31.970 --> 00:26:33.200 align:middle line:90%
It was not energy.

00:26:33.200 --> 00:26:34.880 align:middle line:90%
The energy shock came later.

00:26:34.880 --> 00:26:38.660 align:middle line:84%
But it was supply side,
transport costs, and stuff

00:26:38.660 --> 00:26:41.660 align:middle line:84%
like that, the network, the
production network and things

00:26:41.660 --> 00:26:43.020 align:middle line:90%
like that broke down.

00:26:43.020 --> 00:26:46.230 align:middle line:84%
But they thought it was
going to be very temporary.

00:26:46.230 --> 00:26:49.550 align:middle line:84%
So understanding this model,
they thought, OK, look, this,

00:26:49.550 --> 00:26:53.670 align:middle line:84%
this curve will
come back by itself,

00:26:53.670 --> 00:26:55.290 align:middle line:90%
so better not react right now.

00:26:55.290 --> 00:26:55.790 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:26:55.790 --> 00:26:57.920 align:middle line:84%
Because a recession
is really, this curve

00:26:57.920 --> 00:27:01.480 align:middle line:84%
will come down,
back down by itself.

00:27:01.480 --> 00:27:03.580 align:middle line:84%
Well, the problem is
that it didn't come back

00:27:03.580 --> 00:27:05.610 align:middle line:90%
by itself that fast.

00:27:05.610 --> 00:27:07.600 align:middle line:90%
Some things came up fairly fast.

00:27:07.600 --> 00:27:09.020 align:middle line:90%
Some others did not.

00:27:09.020 --> 00:27:11.500 align:middle line:84%
In particular, labor
force participation

00:27:11.500 --> 00:27:14.810 align:middle line:84%
did not come
sufficiently fast back.

00:27:14.810 --> 00:27:17.470 align:middle line:84%
And so that's the reason
we stayed too long

00:27:17.470 --> 00:27:19.130 align:middle line:90%
in a situation like this.

00:27:19.130 --> 00:27:23.650 align:middle line:84%
And that's one of the main
reasons inflation sort crept up

00:27:23.650 --> 00:27:26.560 align:middle line:84%
in the US, and also in
other places in the world.

00:27:26.560 --> 00:27:31.270 align:middle line:84%
In Europe, the big reason for
why inflation picked up there

00:27:31.270 --> 00:27:33.670 align:middle line:84%
is because this
curve moved a lot up.

00:27:33.670 --> 00:27:34.470 align:middle line:90%
Why is that?

00:27:34.470 --> 00:27:39.941 align:middle line:90%


00:27:39.941 --> 00:27:41.360 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:27:41.360 --> 00:27:42.320 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:27:42.320 --> 00:27:44.720 align:middle line:90%
They had a massive energy shock.

00:27:44.720 --> 00:27:49.410 align:middle line:84%
And so that moved
that curve up a lot.

00:27:49.410 --> 00:27:49.910 align:middle line:90%
Good.

00:27:49.910 --> 00:27:52.530 align:middle line:90%


00:27:52.530 --> 00:27:55.235 align:middle line:84%
I want to now return to
what is going on right now.

00:27:55.235 --> 00:27:57.842 align:middle line:90%


00:27:57.842 --> 00:27:59.800 align:middle line:84%
Actually first, I'm going
to-- yeah, right now,

00:27:59.800 --> 00:28:01.570 align:middle line:90%
meaning the last few days.

00:28:01.570 --> 00:28:04.010 align:middle line:84%
So it turns out
that this diagram

00:28:04.010 --> 00:28:06.970 align:middle line:84%
that I used for the
fiscal consolidation shock

00:28:06.970 --> 00:28:09.790 align:middle line:84%
can also be used to
understand a little bit what

00:28:09.790 --> 00:28:16.840 align:middle line:84%
happens with the Silicon
Valley Bank event.

00:28:16.840 --> 00:28:19.150 align:middle line:84%
Remember, we model
that as a credit shock.

00:28:19.150 --> 00:28:22.260 align:middle line:84%
We said that x we had
is like x going up.

00:28:22.260 --> 00:28:25.400 align:middle line:84%
Well, x going up
does exactly that.

00:28:25.400 --> 00:28:27.730 align:middle line:90%
It moves IS to the left.

00:28:27.730 --> 00:28:36.340 align:middle line:84%
So a shock to x, a panic of
the kind that we saw, is that.

00:28:36.340 --> 00:28:37.490 align:middle line:90%
It moves IS to the left.

00:28:37.490 --> 00:28:39.370 align:middle line:90%
Why is that?

00:28:39.370 --> 00:28:43.060 align:middle line:84%
So for any given level, the
safe, real interest rate,

00:28:43.060 --> 00:28:47.510 align:middle line:84%
a panic, a shock to credit and
so on, moves the IS to the left.

00:28:47.510 --> 00:28:50.248 align:middle line:90%
Why is that?

00:28:50.248 --> 00:28:52.590 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:52.590 --> 00:28:53.718 align:middle line:90%


00:28:53.718 --> 00:28:54.510 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:28:54.510 --> 00:28:57.340 align:middle line:84%
So the safe interest
rate doesn't go up.

00:28:57.340 --> 00:29:04.110 align:middle line:84%
But what goes up is the cost
of borrowing because firms need

00:29:04.110 --> 00:29:06.850 align:middle line:90%
to pay this extra risk premium.

00:29:06.850 --> 00:29:10.020 align:middle line:84%
And then for any given safe
interest rate, the real interest

00:29:10.020 --> 00:29:13.590 align:middle line:84%
rate, firms have
to pay more, which

00:29:13.590 --> 00:29:15.780 align:middle line:84%
means there is less
investment for any given level

00:29:15.780 --> 00:29:16.930 align:middle line:90%
of the real interest rate.

00:29:16.930 --> 00:29:18.760 align:middle line:90%
And so the IS moves to the left.

00:29:18.760 --> 00:29:21.210 align:middle line:84%
And if that happens,
then you start

00:29:21.210 --> 00:29:22.655 align:middle line:90%
getting deflationary forces.

00:29:22.655 --> 00:29:25.190 align:middle line:90%


00:29:25.190 --> 00:29:28.760 align:middle line:84%
So again, all this
happens very quickly here.

00:29:28.760 --> 00:29:32.330 align:middle line:84%
In reality, I told you there
are lots of lags and so on.

00:29:32.330 --> 00:29:35.425 align:middle line:84%
But markets begin to
anticipate what will happen.

00:29:35.425 --> 00:29:38.560 align:middle line:90%


00:29:38.560 --> 00:29:40.360 align:middle line:90%
So markets begin to anticipate.

00:29:40.360 --> 00:29:43.450 align:middle line:84%
So in the immediate,
output doesn't collapse

00:29:43.450 --> 00:29:44.720 align:middle line:90%
immediately or anything.

00:29:44.720 --> 00:29:47.660 align:middle line:84%
And inflation doesn't
collapse immediately.

00:29:47.660 --> 00:29:51.290 align:middle line:84%
But markets realized
that there are long lags.

00:29:51.290 --> 00:29:53.750 align:middle line:90%
But there is a shock already.

00:29:53.750 --> 00:29:56.920 align:middle line:84%
So it's likely that
these things will happen.

00:29:56.920 --> 00:30:00.560 align:middle line:84%
And it's likely that
this will happen.

00:30:00.560 --> 00:30:04.880 align:middle line:84%
And it's also likely that
the Fed will react to that.

00:30:04.880 --> 00:30:06.590 align:middle line:84%
What should be the
reaction of the Fed

00:30:06.590 --> 00:30:08.446 align:middle line:84%
if this stuff gets
to be persistent?

00:30:08.446 --> 00:30:12.850 align:middle line:90%


00:30:12.850 --> 00:30:14.580 align:middle line:84%
How do you get out
of a shock like that

00:30:14.580 --> 00:30:16.080 align:middle line:84%
if you really want
to go back there?

00:30:16.080 --> 00:30:18.940 align:middle line:90%


00:30:18.940 --> 00:30:21.280 align:middle line:90%
You cut interest rates.

00:30:21.280 --> 00:30:24.130 align:middle line:84%
In the case of the US, they
were hiking interest rates

00:30:24.130 --> 00:30:26.630 align:middle line:84%
because we dealing
with high inflation.

00:30:26.630 --> 00:30:31.300 align:middle line:84%
This tells you, well, you should
slow down the pace of hiking.

00:30:31.300 --> 00:30:32.810 align:middle line:84%
Again, they don't
do it immediately.

00:30:32.810 --> 00:30:34.120 align:middle line:90%
They meet next week.

00:30:34.120 --> 00:30:36.420 align:middle line:84%
But the markets don't
need to wait for the Fed.

00:30:36.420 --> 00:30:39.490 align:middle line:84%
They anticipate what
the Fed is likely to do

00:30:39.490 --> 00:30:41.180 align:middle line:90%
and they start betting on that.

00:30:41.180 --> 00:30:44.980 align:middle line:84%
So let me show you
next a bunch of charts

00:30:44.980 --> 00:30:47.770 align:middle line:84%
that show you that
someone in the market

00:30:47.770 --> 00:30:49.762 align:middle line:90%
understands these mechanics--

00:30:49.762 --> 00:30:51.220 align:middle line:84%
a lot of people,
because the prices

00:30:51.220 --> 00:30:53.790 align:middle line:90%
are moving exactly that way.

00:30:53.790 --> 00:30:58.220 align:middle line:90%


00:30:58.220 --> 00:31:04.220 align:middle line:84%
This is something-- this is
the one year ahead inflation

00:31:04.220 --> 00:31:06.530 align:middle line:84%
expectation, as
traded in the market.

00:31:06.530 --> 00:31:09.450 align:middle line:84%
It's called Inflation breakeven,
the one year inflation break.

00:31:09.450 --> 00:31:12.680 align:middle line:84%
So these things are
traded in the market.

00:31:12.680 --> 00:31:15.020 align:middle line:84%
And you can trade
expected inflation

00:31:15.020 --> 00:31:16.740 align:middle line:90%
all the maturities you want.

00:31:16.740 --> 00:31:21.940 align:middle line:84%
So this is what the market was
expecting before this shock.

00:31:21.940 --> 00:31:23.820 align:middle line:84%
We're getting hotter
and hotter numbers.

