00:42:21.520 --> 00:42:25.430 align:middle line:84%
So this is exactly what
I was telling you before.

00:42:25.430 --> 00:42:27.700 align:middle line:84%
The market is
anticipating that we

00:42:27.700 --> 00:42:33.550 align:middle line:84%
had a huge contraction in the
IS because x went up a lot.

00:42:33.550 --> 00:42:37.250 align:middle line:84%
The major consequences, that
is going to be lower inflation.

00:42:37.250 --> 00:42:38.920 align:middle line:90%
Yes, we have a problem.

00:42:38.920 --> 00:42:45.780 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if the US did not
have 5.5% of inflation today,

00:42:45.780 --> 00:42:48.280 align:middle line:84%
I can assure you that the Fed
would have come out and said,

00:42:48.280 --> 00:42:50.230 align:middle line:90%
we cut the rates right now.

00:42:50.230 --> 00:42:52.600 align:middle line:84%
The only reason they're
not cutting right now

00:42:52.600 --> 00:42:54.560 align:middle line:90%
is because we have two problems.

00:42:54.560 --> 00:42:56.298 align:middle line:84%
We have the financial
panic on one side

00:42:56.298 --> 00:42:58.340 align:middle line:84%
and we have the high
inflation on the other side.

00:42:58.340 --> 00:43:01.430 align:middle line:84%
So they have to balance
these two forces.

00:43:01.430 --> 00:43:03.655 align:middle line:84%
But the expectation
of the market

00:43:03.655 --> 00:43:05.030 align:middle line:84%
is that the balance
of two forces

00:43:05.030 --> 00:43:08.090 align:middle line:84%
is going to be dominated by the
contraction in aggregate demand

00:43:08.090 --> 00:43:10.960 align:middle line:84%
much sooner than
people were expecting.

00:43:10.960 --> 00:43:13.390 align:middle line:84%
So that's what the market
is pricing at the moment.

00:43:13.390 --> 00:43:14.890 align:middle line:84%
And what I'm saying
is, I was trying

00:43:14.890 --> 00:43:24.410 align:middle line:84%
to highlight that this is
very consistent with that.

00:43:24.410 --> 00:43:26.330 align:middle line:84%
It's just the market
looking ahead,

00:43:26.330 --> 00:43:28.510 align:middle line:90%
but what is likely to happen.

00:43:28.510 --> 00:43:29.950 align:middle line:84%
It started from
a situation which

00:43:29.950 --> 00:43:32.075 align:middle line:84%
is a little bit more
complicated, again, because we

00:43:32.075 --> 00:43:33.650 align:middle line:90%
already had high inflation.

00:43:33.650 --> 00:43:35.270 align:middle line:90%
Well, I do not know, really.

00:43:35.270 --> 00:43:39.370 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it is on one
hand, more complicated

00:43:39.370 --> 00:43:42.670 align:middle line:84%
because we have a problem
of high inflation.

00:43:42.670 --> 00:43:45.897 align:middle line:84%
On the other hand,
having high inflation

00:43:45.897 --> 00:43:47.980 align:middle line:84%
allows you to cut the real
interest rate much more

00:43:47.980 --> 00:43:48.700 align:middle line:90%
aggressively.

00:43:48.700 --> 00:43:50.920 align:middle line:84%
Because if you bring the
nominal interest rate to 0

00:43:50.920 --> 00:43:53.200 align:middle line:84%
and you have
inflation of 5%, that

00:43:53.200 --> 00:43:55.940 align:middle line:84%
allows you to cut the
real interest rate to -5%.

00:43:55.940 --> 00:43:57.430 align:middle line:84%
Well, if you start
with a situation

00:43:57.430 --> 00:44:00.360 align:middle line:84%
where your inflation is 0,
you don't have any space

00:44:00.360 --> 00:44:01.610 align:middle line:90%
to cut the real interest rate.

00:44:01.610 --> 00:44:04.377 align:middle line:84%
So the Fed can be
very aggressive here.

00:44:04.377 --> 00:44:06.710 align:middle line:84%
And the only reason is not
being very, very aggressive--

00:44:06.710 --> 00:44:09.085 align:middle line:84%
They were very aggressive in
terms of supporting deposits

00:44:09.085 --> 00:44:09.950 align:middle line:90%
and all that.

00:44:09.950 --> 00:44:15.790 align:middle line:84%
But they can be very aggressive
in terms of interest rate cuts

00:44:15.790 --> 00:44:17.270 align:middle line:90%
if the need arises.

00:44:17.270 --> 00:44:18.200 align:middle line:90%
Hopefully we won't.

00:44:18.200 --> 00:44:20.140 align:middle line:84%
But they have a
space because we're

00:44:20.140 --> 00:44:22.150 align:middle line:84%
starting from a much
higher level of inflation.

00:44:22.150 --> 00:44:23.680 align:middle line:90%
That helps.

00:44:23.680 --> 00:44:27.070 align:middle line:84%
It hurts in the sense that
it will delay the reaction.

00:44:27.070 --> 00:44:28.810 align:middle line:84%
But it helps in the
sense that they have

00:44:28.810 --> 00:44:31.245 align:middle line:90%
much more space for policy.

00:44:31.245 --> 00:44:35.640 align:middle line:90%


00:44:35.640 --> 00:44:36.455 align:middle line:90%
What is this?

00:44:36.455 --> 00:44:40.720 align:middle line:90%


00:44:40.720 --> 00:44:43.910 align:middle line:84%
This is just one
year interest rates.

00:44:43.910 --> 00:44:47.600 align:middle line:84%
That reflects the
previous picture, as well.

00:44:47.600 --> 00:44:50.110 align:middle line:90%


00:44:50.110 --> 00:44:57.340 align:middle line:84%
One year out rates were over
5% a few days ago and now are

00:44:57.340 --> 00:44:59.530 align:middle line:90%
in the low 4s.

00:44:59.530 --> 00:45:02.860 align:middle line:84%
And this picture I kept
updating, as you can see.

00:45:02.860 --> 00:45:04.335 align:middle line:90%
It was really dropping fast.

00:45:04.335 --> 00:45:07.330 align:middle line:90%


00:45:07.330 --> 00:45:08.890 align:middle line:90%
That's a big change.

00:45:08.890 --> 00:45:12.195 align:middle line:84%
The one year rate, 60 basis
points, that's a big change.

00:45:12.195 --> 00:45:15.680 align:middle line:90%


00:45:15.680 --> 00:45:18.080 align:middle line:90%
So that's where we're at.

00:45:18.080 --> 00:45:20.610 align:middle line:84%
And from the next lecture, I'm
going to start with growth.

00:45:20.610 --> 00:45:21.950 align:middle line:90%
But any questions about this?

00:45:21.950 --> 00:45:25.780 align:middle line:90%


00:45:25.780 --> 00:45:26.280 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:26.280 --> 00:45:28.510 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to start
growth now in four minutes.

00:45:28.510 --> 00:45:31.020 align:middle line:84%
But so the set of
topics we're going

00:45:31.020 --> 00:45:35.310 align:middle line:84%
to discuss from the next
lecture are very different,

00:45:35.310 --> 00:45:37.660 align:middle line:84%
subject to not having
any major events.

00:45:37.660 --> 00:45:40.590 align:middle line:84%
If there is a major event,
I'm going to reshuffle things

00:45:40.590 --> 00:45:44.550 align:middle line:84%
so we can talk about financial
panics and things of that kind.

00:45:44.550 --> 00:45:46.440 align:middle line:84%
Let's hope that it can
stick to the program

00:45:46.440 --> 00:45:50.020 align:middle line:90%
and do growth in the next week.

00:45:50.020 --> 00:45:51.600 align:middle line:90%
OK, good.

00:45:51.600 --> 00:45:53.450 align:middle line:90%
Have a good weekend.

